[[File:Omiwa-jinja (Ichinomiya) torii.JPG|thumb|220px|right|Torii]]
'''Ōmiwa Shrine''' (おおみわじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Hanaike, Ichinomiya, Aichi Prefecture. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} ({{ill|lt=Myojin Taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}}), and styles itself as {{ill|lt=Owari Province|Q514506|WD=Q514506|1=Owari Province}}{{ill|lt=Ichinomiya|Q1656379|WD=Q1656379|1=Ichinomiya}}.

=== Enshrined deity ===
The enshrined deity is the following{{Sfn|大神神社（平凡社）|1981年}}.
* '''{{ill|WD=Q10936701|lt=Ōmononushi|Q10936701|WD=Q10936701|WD=Q10936701|lt=Ōmononushi-no-Kami|1=Ōmononushi}}'''
*: A deity worshipped by the {{ill|lt=Ōmiwa clan|Q11438330|WD=Q11438330|1=Miwa clan}} (Miwa clan), and the deity of {{ill|lt=Ōmiwa Shrine|Q705542|WD=Q705542|1=Ōmiwa Shrine}} (Sakurai, Nara){{Sfn|大神神社（平凡社）|1981年}}.

Apart from Ōmononushi, a theory identifies the deity as Ōmiwatsune-no-Mikoto (seen in the '{{ill|lt=Shinsen Shōjiroku|Q1045362|WD=Q1045362|1=Shinsen Shōjiroku}}'), suggesting common ancestry between the {{ill|lt=Owari clan|Q11465311|WD=Q11465311|1=Owari clan}} and this shrine’s worship clan{{Sfn|大神神社（平凡社）|1981年}}.

=== History ===
Founding unknown. Until the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Edo period|1=Edo period|WD=Q184963}} it was called '''Sanmyōjin''' or '''Sannomiya Myōjin'''{{Sfn|大神神社（平凡社）|1981年}}. It is identified with “Ōmiwa Shrine, Myojin-grand” in Nakashima District, Owari Province, in the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}'{{Sfn|大神神社（平凡社）|1981年}}. Depending on manuscript, name appears as “Ōkami-gami-sha” or “Taisha.”

Unlike other Myojin-grand shrines, it is not listed in the Myojin-festival section of the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}' temporary rites, leading to a view that “Myojin-grand” in Jinmyōchō is an interpolation. The affirmative view infers it joined Myojin-grand rank after completion of '{{ill|lt=Jōgan-shiki|Q11634547|WD=Q11634547|1=Jōgan-shiki}}' and temporary ritual codes{{Sfn|大神神社（平凡社）|1981年}}.

In Meiji 5 ({{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|WD=Q7753|1=1872}}) May, it was ranked {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Gōsha|1=UNKNOWN}} under the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=modern shrine rank system|1=UNKNOWN}}{{Sfn|明治神社誌料|1912年}}. Today it claims Owari Ichinomiya and belongs to the National Ichinomiya Association (though generally Owari Ichinomiya is {{ill|lt=Masumida Shrine|Q705916|WD=Q705916|1=Masumida Shrine}}). The shrine side argues Masumida and Ōmiwa were paired shrines and both became Ichinomiya.

=== Divine ranks ===
All written as “Ōmiwa Myōjin.” Rank varies by manuscript.
* Senior First Rank ('Owari no Kuni Jinmyōchō' Atsuta text)
* Junior First Rank ('Owari no Kuni Jinmyōchō' Mizō-in and Tenbun texts)
* Senior Second Rank Upper ('Owari no Kuni Jinmyōchō' Kōnomiya text)

=== Sessha and massha ===
Current six:
* Rokusho-sha
* Mishima-sha
* Hakusan-sha
* Shinmei-sha
* Shōkon-sha
* Susano-sha

=== Cultural properties ===
=== Ichinomiya City-designated Tangible Cultural Property ===
* One pair of wooden komainu (sculpture)

=== Other ===
As shrine treasures, there are 3 swords kept at Ichinomiya City Museum.

=== Local information ===
; Address
* Hanaike 2-15-28, Ichinomiya, Aichi

; Access
* Rail
** About 5 minutes on foot from {{ill|lt=Myōkōji Station|Q6949401|WD=Q6949401|1=Myōkōji Station}} on Meitetsu Nagoya Main Line.
** About 20 minutes on foot from {{ill|lt=Meitetsu Ichinomiya Station|Q2856589|WD=Q2856589|1=Meitetsu Ichinomiya Station}}.
** About 20 minutes on foot from JR {{ill|lt=Owari-Ichinomiya Station|Q871495|WD=Q871495|1=Owari-Ichinomiya Station}}.

